So to explain the scoring again (and this is all in the readme)... there are 4 major components making up your score.. Availability -- Is your subtensor running and is it reachable by external source.  Reliability -- how well is your subtensor responding to challenges (usually via retrieving latest block from the subtensor) and if it is accurate/correct.  Latency -- How fast is your subtensor able to respond to the request.. this is directly impacted by your system config... if your sytem overall is performing poorly, this score will be low.  Latency score is also scaled against the location between your miner and the validator that is scoring you to be normalized.  Last one Distribution -- this is indicating how many subtensor/miner nodes are running in your region.. again this subnet is trying to promote distributing nodes as widely as possible.. if all the miners are situated in the US for example.. that doesn't help decentralize the network..
if you find your distribution score low.. then think about setting miner in a different / more remote region...

This is a high level overview of what I typically will do when considering to mine a subnet or not. 

I look at estimated daily earnings in tao stats plus the cost of mining hardware and estimate my break even point in days.  If the breakeven point makes sense based on my goals and risk tolerance then I decide to mine. I also consider the potential emissions for the subnet based on what they have built, what they are building, and how much I believe in the team.

I ask myself questions like... does the team seem dedicated,  do they provide support, how much effort did they put into their documentation,  what value does the subnet add to Bittensor, how difficult is it to setup and mine etc.
I also think it's important to consider multiple factors when choosing the subnet to mine
part of my concern is that I don't know if the specs of my CPU are good enough to stay online once the subnet is full...
and it looks like it will be full very soon

I also look at the difficulty to mine and who the competition will be and if I have the skillset to compete... Does this subnet require constant AI model tuning where the AI engineers will dominate or can I setup a default model and tweak a few settings within my skills to try to find little edges?

No one ever knows that with any of the subnets, that's part of the game. Naturally over time people will find different areas to optimize their scores. As we continue to develop and grow, we will also adjust the incentive mechanism such as adding details to the distribution. This could be measuring regions instead of countries or adding more weights to regions that will have higher demand.  People will need to adjust to things. That's a big part of what makes mining TAO different than other tokens. Mining tao is having subnets, models, miners and everything about the network constantly improving.
